The result was the Theodosian code, pro· mulgated in February au. 438, with statutory force srom and alter the commencement ol au. 439, as the only authority lor the ‘ius principale,’ or imperial legislation, from Constantine I to that date. It consisted oi sixteen books, arranged separately in Tities and rubrics, and the constitutions in each Title were placed in chronological order. The first live books were arranged on the plan ol the commentaries on the Edict, and contained most os the enactments relating to private law. The sixth to the eighth books consist principally oi constitutional and administrativa ordinances ; the ninth is criminal law; the tenth and eleventh relate to the financial system, and in part to procedure; the twellth to the fifteenth, to the constitution and administration of towns and other corporations, and the sixteenth conmins the eonsti- tutions which deal with the church and the ecclesiastical system in general. This code was accepted in the West as well as in the East, and partly thus, partly by the ‘law of Citations' oi twelve years* earlier date, unilonnity os law was secured throughout the two halves ol the empire.
